Tractography with dipy and the Stanford DWI data - Extended Tutorial

Thu 18 June 2015

The following is a basic introduction to doing tractography with the dipy (diffusion imaging in python) library. It is essentially an augmented version of the connectivity matrices tutorial on the dipy website, the principal augmentations being a) the use of an alternative parcellation scheme (the multi-resolution Lausanne2008 atlas), and b) the extension to whole-brain (rather than corpus-callosum ROI) connectivity. I've also added in some notes on trackvis visualizations, pandas dataframes, and various other useful tidbids.

There is a lot more to the process, theory, and practice of diffusion MRI and tractography than described here. We completely skip most raw data and preprocessing considerations, think very little about the actual tractography algorithms and what it produces, and make a bee line for whole-brain connectivity matrices. Those new to diffusion MRI and/or tractography should ideally, in the fullness of time, familiarize themselves more with these other dimensions, as and when they use these techniques in their research.

Dipy example part 1: tutorial from the website¶

This section is a slightly modified version of a tutorial from the dipy website, which gives a brief, but for our purposes entirely adequate, demonstration of how to use the software to compute tractography streamlines from (almost) raw data, and then how to generate a 'structural connectome' for modified freesurfer 'aparc' parcellation.

Passages where I have unapologetically lifted the text and code verbatim from the tutorial example are given in quotation (indented and italicized) text. These comprise most of the text and code in this section, with the exception of a few added remarks and augmentations.

The subsequent section is an extension of the website tutorial analysis. It uses (mostly) the same data and variables, but extends it to a whole brain analysis, as well as computation and visualization of connectivity matrix eigenmodes.

Load in the data¶

#%load http://nipy.org/dipy/_downloads/streamline_tools.py

Connectivity Matrices, ROI Intersections and Density Maps

This example is meant to be an introduction to some of the streamline tools available in dipy. Some of the functions covered in this example are target, connectivity_matrix and density_map. target allows one to filter streamlines that either pass through or do not pass through some region of the brain, connectivity_matrix groups and counts streamlines based on where in the brain they begin and end, and finally, density map counts the number of streamlines that pass though every voxel of some image.

To get started we'll need to have a set of streamlines to work with. We'll use EuDX along with the CsaOdfModel to make some streamlines. Let's import the modules and download the data we'll be using.

The dipy tutorial makes use of the following commands to grab the data and read it in to the namespace:


hardi_img, gtab, labels_img = read_stanford_labels()
data = hardi_img.get_data()
labels = labels_img.get_data()

fetch_stanford_t1()
t1 = read_stanford_t1()
t1 = read_stanford_t1()
t1_data = t1.get_data()

Fit the voxel-level diffusion model and run tractography¶

*We've loaded an image called labels_img which is a map of tissue types such that every integer value in the array labels represents an anatomical structure or tissue type [#]_. For this example, the image was created so that white matter voxels have values of either 1 or 2. We'll use peaks_from_model to apply the CsaOdfModel to each white matter voxel and estimate fiber orientations which we can use for tracking.*

white_matter = (labels == 1) | (labels == 2)
csamodel = shm.CsaOdfModel(gtab, 6)
csapeaks = peaks.peaks_from_model(model=csamodel,
                                  data=data,
                                  sphere=peaks.default_sphere,
                                  relative_peak_threshold=.8,
                                  min_separation_angle=45,
                                  mask=white_matter);

Now we can use EuDX to track all of the white matter. To keep things reasonably fast we use density=2 which will result in 8 seeds per voxel. We'll set a_low (the parameter which determines the threshold of FA/QA under which tracking stops) to be very low because we've already applied a white matter mask.

seeds = utils.seeds_from_mask(white_matter, density=2)
streamline_generator = EuDX(csapeaks.peak_values, csapeaks.peak_indices,
                            odf_vertices=peaks.default_sphere.vertices,
                            a_low=.05, step_sz=.5, seeds=seeds)
affine = streamline_generator.affine
streamlines = list(streamline_generator);

The first of the tracking utilities we'll cover here is target. This function takes a set of streamlines and a region of interest (ROI) and returns only those streamlines that pass though the ROI. The ROI should be an array such that the voxels that belong to the ROI are True and all other voxels are False (this type of binary array is sometimes called a mask). This function can also exclude all the streamlines that pass though an ROI by setting the include flag to False. In this example we'll target the streamlines of the corpus callosum. Our labels array has a sagittal slice of the corpus callosum identified by the label value 2. We'll create an ROI mask from that label and create two sets of streamlines, those that intersect with the ROI and those that don't.

cc_slice = labels == 2
cc_streamlines = utils.target(streamlines, cc_slice, affine=affine)
cc_streamlines = list(cc_streamlines)

other_streamlines = utils.target(streamlines, cc_slice, affine=affine,
                                 include=False)
other_streamlines = list(other_streamlines)

Once we've targeted on the corpus callosum ROI, we might want to find out which regions of the brain are connected by these streamlines. To do this we can use the connectivity_matrix function. This function takes a set of streamlines and an array of labels as arguments. It returns the number of streamlines that start and end at each pair of labels and it can return the streamlines grouped by their endpoints. Notice that this function only considers the endpoints of each streamline.

We can also use trackvis for streamline visualizations, which can be more convenient than the fvtk option above (it is, after all, a far more mature piece of software that is very widely used). In particular, it allows interactive visualization, which is very handy for deciding which screenshot is most informative.

To demo trackvis (and the associated command line program track_vis), we need to skip ahead to the end of the dipy tutorial, which shows how to save streamlines to a .trk file. I'm going to insert that part in here now so we can see the results next to the fvtk visualizations. See below for a bit more explanation of this.

def save_to_trk(tracks,labels_img,outfname,affine):

  # Make a trackvis header so we can save streamlines
  voxel_size = labels_img.get_header().get_zooms()
  trackvis_header = nib.trackvis.empty_header()
  trackvis_header['voxel_size'] = voxel_size
  trackvis_header['dim'] = labels_img.shape
  trackvis_header['voxel_order'] = "RAS"

  # Move streamlines to "trackvis space"
  trackvis_point_space = utils.affine_for_trackvis(voxel_size)
  trk = list(utils.move_streamlines(tracks,trackvis_point_space, input_space=affine))
  
  # Save streamlines
  for_save = [(sl, None, None) for sl in trk]
  nib.trackvis.write(outfname, for_save, trackvis_header)

The above examples show a very important thing to know about using trackvis: by default, the program will 'skip' some variable percentage of the number of actual streamlines in the .trk file. In general, this is done in a smart way that doesn't change the appearance of the tracks, apart from to make them less dense (hence easier to see the overall structure). There is good logic to it. But it is a bit sneaky.

We can also get trackvis to output movie frames. Occasionally these can be a useful and succinct way of visualizing anatomical structures. Just as often, they can be a bit of a faff-distraction opportunity; so beware...

I've personally found the process of making movies and embedding them in ipython/jupyter notebooks and webpages to be a bit hit-and-miss, in terms of which codecs work, etc. Using .gif files, rather than .avi or .mp4, does seem to be a bist more robust, at least at the time of writing. Trackvis is great for interactive visualization. If however you want to completely remove the iteractive element, you can use the track_vis program, which essentially exposes all of trackvis's visualization functionalities with a command line interface.

def get_track_vis_pic(trk_file, length=None,bg_image=None,bz=None, sc='/tmp/movie_frame',
                      rois=None,bo=None,bc='0 0 0',tr=None,azim=0,elev=0,aa=False,
                      tc=None,showbox=False):

  #track_vis tracks.trk -l 20 -b recon_dwi.img -bz 1
  #track_vis tracks.trk -l 20 -sc movie/frame.png 1    
  
    
  # remove tmp.cam from current directory, if it's there
  !rm tmp.cam
    
  cmd = 'track_vis ' + trk_file
  if length: cmd+= ' -l %s' %length
  if bg_image: cmd+= ' -b ' + bg_image
  if bz: cmd+= ' -bz %s ' %bz
  if sc: cmd+= ' -sc %s.png 1'  %sc
  cmd+= ' -bc ' + bc
                    
  if rois: 
    cmd+= ' -rois '
    for r in rois: cmd+=' %s %s ' %(r[0],r[1])

  if tr:

  if aa: cmd+= ' -aa '
       
  if showbox: cmd+= ' -box ' 
    
  cmd+= ' -camera azimuth %s elevation %s' %(azim,elev)
      
  cmd+= ' -na '
        
  print '\ntrack_vis call: \n\n%s' %cmd
  res = %system $cmd
            
  print '\n\nres: \n\n%s ' %res

There a lots of customization options for track_vis, the vast majority of which are left out of the above example to keep things simple. It should hopefully be clear how to customize to add further command line arguments without too much pain.

Here are the track_vis command line options:

!track_vis --help

track_vis 0.8.1, build 2012.09.20

Usage: track_vis TRACK_DATA_FILE [OPTION(s)]...

Filtering (selecting tracks to display) options:
  -l, --length_threshold <low_th> <high_th>
           set length thresholds in millimeter for the tracks to display,
           only those with length between theshold1 and theshold2 are 
           displayed.
           default values are 0 and infinity
  -nx, --sagittal_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
  -ny, --coronal_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
  -nz, --axial_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
           display only those tracks that cross a given slice or a slab
           of slices. slice number starts from 1
  -ex, --end_sagittal_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
  -ey, --end_coronal_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
  -ez, --end_axial_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
           display only those tracks that end in a given slice or a slab
           of slices. slice number starts from 1
  -mx, --minus_sagittal_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
  -my, --minus_coronal_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
  -mz, --minus_axial_slice <start_number> [<end_number>]
           display only those tracks that do not cross a given slice or a slab
           of slices. slice number starts from 1
  -roi, --roi <file name> <low_threshold> <high_threshold>
           display only those tracks that pass through a roi. roi file
           must in nifti/analyze format. default low threshold is 0.5 and high
           threshold is infinity
  -roi2, --roi2 <file name> <low_threshold> <high_threshold>
           display only those tracks that pass through roi and roi2. roi files
           must in nifti/analyze format
  -roi_pt, --roi_pointer <x> <y> <z> <radius> <no_display>
  -roi_pt2, --roi_pointer2 <x> <y> <z> <radius> <no_display>
           use a voxel index (x, y, z) and radius to define a roi. all values
           are integers. default values are 1, 1, 1 and 1, respectively
  -roi_end, --roi_end <file name> <low> <high_threshold> <both_ends>
           display only those tracks that ends in the roi with both or either
           end(s). default value for both_ends is 0, which means either end
           can end in the roi
  -roi_end2, --roi_end2 <file name> <low> <high_threshold> <both_ends>
           display only those tracks that ends in the roi and roi2 with both or
           either end(s). default value for both_ends is 0, which means either
           end can end in the roi
  -end_pt, --end_point <number_of_iterations>
           use the end point voxels of the selected tracks as an end roi
           and do tracking. repeat this process by given number of times.
           default number of iterations is 1
  -roi_disk, --roi_disk <pt_x> <pt_y> <pt_z> <radius> <v_x> <v_y> <v_z>
                        <angle_th1> <angle_th2> <no_display>
           use a disk as roi. the disk is defined by a center point, a normal 
           vector and the radius, in voxel size. angle threshold is defined 
           as the tolerance angle between the line segment that touches the 
           disk and the normal vector, in degree. default angle_th1 is
           0 degree and angle_th2 is 90 degree, which means accepting all
  -roi_tube, --roi_tube <radius> <angle_threshold> <number_of_disk> 
                        <track_number> <no_display>
           use a track to construct a series of disk rois (or tube). 
           the procedure goes like this:
           first go through all other filters/rois to get a group of tracks,
           then use the <track_number>-ith track from that group and construct 
           a series of disks with <radius> and <angle_threshold> along the 
           track. use those disks as roi to re-filter the tracks. if 
           track_number is smaller than 1, use all the tracks of that group.
           default value of <radius> is 1 (voxel), <angle_threshold> is 90 
           degree, <number_of_disk> is 10 and <track_number> is 0 (all)
  -roi_tube_iteration, --roi_tube_iteration <number_of_iterations>

           NOTE: horriblely slow! even just for 2 iterations. default value 1

                      <x_offset> <y_offset> <z_offset>
           apply a lattice-shaped roi on top of other rois. x, y and z are 
           thickness in pixels and x_space, y_space and z_space are spacing in
           pixels. minimum value for <x/y/z> and <x/y/z_space> is 1 and 
           <x/y/z_offset> is 0.
           note: this option only applys when an roi is provided
  -u, --u_factor_threshold <low_th> <high_th>
           set u factor thresholds for the tracks to display, only those
           with u factors between thesholds are displayed. u factor 
           defines U-shapeness of the track. 
           u factor ranges from -1 to 1. default values are -1 and 1
  -curvature, --curvature <low_th> <high_th>
           set curvature thresholds for the tracks to display
  -torsion, --torsion <low_th> <high_th>

  -kt, --kt <low_th> <high_th>

  -skipp, --skipp <s> <n>

Camera and screen capture options: 
  -save_cam, --save_camera <filename>
           save the last camera position to file. always use .cam extension
           by default save to tmp.cam to current directory. if filename is
           'none', no camera file will be saved
  -load_cam, --load_camera <filename>
           load camera position from file. by default load tmp.cam from 
           current directory. 
           note: if both -load_cam and -camera(or -offset) options are given,
           -load_cam is proceeded first
  -camera, --camera_action <action1> <parameter1> <action2> <parameter2>...
           set the initial camera position by setting up a series actions.
           the available actions are - 
               azimuth <angle>
                  rotate the camera around the view-up vector centered
                  at the focal point to some degree. angle is in degree
               elevation <angle>
                  rotate camera about the cross product of the direction
                  of projection and the view-up vector centered on the 
                  focal point to some degree. angle is in degree
               dolly <scale>
                  set initial viewing position by moving the camera along
                  the direction of projection. scale greater than 1 means
                  moving towards the focal point. scale less than 1 means
                  moving away from the focal point
           the action are performed in given order. that is, action1 is
           performed first and action2 is second, etc.
  -offset, --offset <sag> <cor> <axial>
           set offset position of the focal point, in milli-meters. default 
           values are 0 0 0
  -sc, --screen_capture <filename/prefix> <start_num> 
                        <angle_step> <total_angle> <paddings>
           capture the rendering window to a graphics file or a series of 
           graphics files if at least start_num is provided (default angle 
           step is 1 degree, total angle is 360 and the filename number 
           padding is 4). support jpg, png, tiff, bmp and ps. use png if no 
           file extension given.
           for example -sc frame.png 1 1 will save a series of image files
           named frame0001.png, frame0002.png, etc., till the camera rotated
           360 degrees along view up vector
           note: when this option enabled, interaction will be disabled
           the program will end right after the images are saved.
  -mag, --magnification <factor>
           magnification factor for output. when capturing window 
           screen to image file, the image size is determined by the 
           size of the render window multiplied by the magnification
           factor. for example, if the render window size is 1000x800 
           and mag factor is 2, the actual image size saved is 2000x1600.
           that allows to save huge size screen shot image even if the

In our example track there are more streamlines connecting regions 11 and 54 than any other pair of regions. These labels represent the left and right superior frontal gyrus respectively. However, the interpretation of streamline counts can be tricky. The relationship between the underlying biology and the streamline counts will depend on several factors, including how the tracking was done, and the correct way to interpret these kinds of connectivity matrices is still an open question in the diffusion imaging literature.

Write to .trk file¶

Now write the superior frontal track to .trk file

# Make a trackvis header so we can save streamlines
voxel_size = labels_img.get_header().get_zooms()
trackvis_header = nib.trackvis.empty_header()
trackvis_header['voxel_size'] = voxel_size
trackvis_header['dim'] = shape
trackvis_header['voxel_order'] = "RAS"


# Move streamlines to "trackvis space"
trackvis_point_space = utils.affine_for_trackvis(voxel_size)
lr_sf_trk = utils.move_streamlines(lr_superiorfrontal_track,
                                   trackvis_point_space, input_space=affine)
lr_sf_trk = list(lr_sf_trk)


# Save streamlines
lr_sf_trk_file = outdir + "/lr-superiorfrontal.trk"

for_save = [(sl, None, None) for sl in lr_sf_trk]
nib.trackvis.write(lr_sf_trk_file, for_save, trackvis_header)

*Let's take a moment here to consider the representation of streamlines used in dipy. Streamlines are a path though the 3d space of an image represented by a set of points. For these points to have a meaningful interpretation, these points must be given in a known coordinate system. The affine attribute of the streamline_generator object specifies the coordinate system of the points with respect to the voxel indices of the input data. trackvis_point_space specifies the trackvis coordinate system with respect to the same indices. The move_streamlines function returns a new set of streamlines from an existing set of streamlines in the target space. The target space and the input space must be specified as affine transformations with respect to the same reference [#]_. If no input space is given, the input space will be the same as the current representation of the streamlines, in other words the input space is assumed to be np.eye(4), the 4-by-4 identity matrix.*

All of the functions above that allow streamlines to interact with volumes take an affine argument. This argument allows these functions to work with streamlines regardless of their coordinate system. For example even though we moved our streamlines to "trackvis space", we can still compute the density map as long as we specify the right coordinate system.

dm_trackvis = utils.density_map(lr_sf_trk, shape, affine=trackvis_point_space)
assert np.all(dm == dm_trackvis)

This means that streamlines can interact with any image volume, for example a high resolution structural image, as long as one can register that image to the diffusion images and calculate the coordinate system with respect to that image.

Footnotes:

.. [#] The image aparc-reduced.nii.gz, which we load as labels_img, is a modified version of label map aparc+aseg.mgz created by freesurfer. The corpus callosum region is a combination of the freesurfer labels 251-255. The remaining freesurfer labels were re-mapped and reduced so that they lie between 0 and 88. To see the freesurfer region, label and name, represented by each value see label_info.txt in ~/.dipy/stanford_hardi.
.. [#] An affine transformation is a mapping between two coordinate systems that can represent scaling, rotation, sheer, translation and reflection. Affine transformations are often represented using a 4x4 matrix where the last row of the matrix is [0, 0, 0, 1].

Make single-hemisphere connectivity matrices¶

(0_0) 
# (note: I've included the incorrect spelling of hippocampus as that is what 
#  is in the labels)
subctx_names = ['thalamusproper', 'caudate', 'pallidum', 'putamen', 'accumbensarea', 
                'hyppocampus', 'hippocampus', 'brainstem'] #, 'amygdala']

_dfMs_lh = {}; _dfMs_rh = {}
_dfMs_lh_ctx = {}; _dfMs_rh_ctx = {}
for _sc in _scales:
  _dfMs_lh[_sc] = _dfMs[_sc].filter(like='lh', axis=0).filter(like='lh', axis=1)
  _dfMs_rh[_sc] = _dfMs[_sc].filter(like='rh', axis=0).filter(like='rh', axis=1)    


  # for the cortical-only dataframes, remove any column and row entries from the above 
  # two dataframes whose names match the 'subctx_names' list:
  _dfMs_lh_ctx[_sc] = _dfMs_lh[_sc].copy()
  vals = _dfMs_lh[_sc].columns.get_level_values('label')
  droppers = [dv for dv in vals for s in subctx_names if s in dv]
  _dfMs_lh_ctx[_sc].drop(droppers,level='label', axis=1,inplace=True)
  _dfMs_lh_ctx[_sc].drop(droppers,level='label', axis=0,inplace=True)
    
    
  _dfMs_rh_ctx[_sc] = _dfMs_rh[_sc].copy()
  vals = _dfMs_rh[_sc].columns.get_level_values('label')
  droppers = [dv for dv in vals for s in subctx_names if s in dv]
  _dfMs_rh_ctx[_sc].drop(droppers,level='label', axis=1,inplace=True)
  _dfMs_rh_ctx[_sc].drop(droppers,level='label', axis=0, inplace=True)

Now save these left hemisphere, right hemisphere, left hemisphere cortical-only and right hemisphere cortical-only connectivity matrix dataframes to file:

(0_0) 
for _sc in _scales:
  _outfile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_lh_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_lh[_sc].to_pickle(_outfile)
  
  _outfile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_rh_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_rh[_sc].to_pickle(_outfile)
      
  _outfile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_lh_ctx_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_lh_ctx[_sc].to_pickle(_outfile)
  
  _outfile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_rh_ctx_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_rh_ctx[_sc].to_pickle(_outfile)

As above with the full dataframes, these can be loaded back in with the following:

(0_0) 
# (and it's instantaneous to do so, so we'll leave it uncommented for clarity):
_dfMs_lh = {}; _dfMs_rh = {}; _dfMs_lh_ctx = {}; _dfMs_rh_ctx = {}
_scales = [33,60,125,250,500]
for _sc in _scales:
  _infile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_lh_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_lh[_sc] = pd.read_pickle(_infile)
  
  _infile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_rh_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_rh[_sc] = pd.read_pickle(_infile)
      
  _infile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_lh_ctx_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_lh_ctx[_sc] = pd.read_pickle(_infile)
  
  _infile = outdir + '/l2k8_connectivity_matrix_rh_ctx_scale%s.pkl' %_sc
  _dfMs_rh_ctx[_sc] = pd.read_pickle(_infile)
